                    </div>
                    <span>I have been busilly reading a book I bought at the airport in Korea (for only 19000 korean won) called "What went wrong?", by a (quote) "towering figure among experts of the Muslim world". I don't think they realised the pun ("twin towers - tower-ing figure"). His thesis is basically that the Muslims hate the West because the supremacy of Islamic culture was eclipsed by the West in the 14th to 18th centuries, and they can't come to terms with being overtaken by infidel. Maybe so, but this Prrinceton Prroffessor (excuse the spit) neglects to mention that U.S. Occupation of the Middle East might also be pissing them off. In fact, the word "oil" appears nowhere in this book, even though it talks of events up to and after Sept 11 2001. He mentions Usama Bin Laden (and to his credit he spells the name correctly), but not the fact that Usama objects to U.S. military forces stationed in the Muslim holy land. U.S.A is not mentioned in any context other than being the victim of unreasoning psycopathic hatred by a bunch of cultural has-beens who can't accept the fact.<P>But to give the book it's due, it IS an interesting account of the Moslem World from the 14th to 18th centuries.</span>
                  
              
